 sources, Keel demonstrates that Christian ideas about creation, ancestry, and universalism helped form the basis of modern scientific accounts of human diversity-despite the ostensible shift in modern biology towards scientific naturalism, objectivity, and value neutrality. By showing the connections between Christian thought and scientific racial thinking, this book calls into question the notion that science and religion are mutually exclusive intellectual domains and proposes that the advance of modern science did not follow a linear process of secularization.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 0aEurocentrismxHistory. 0aRacexHistoriography. 0aRacexReligious aspectsxChristianity. 0aReligion and sciencexHistory. 4aChristianity. 4abiology. 4acritical race theory. 4aevolution. 4agenetics. 4ahealth science. 4amongrel epistemology. 4apolygenism. 4ascientific racism. 4asecularization. 7aHISTORY / Social History.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311070368940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781503604377zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503604377423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781503604377.jpg  a978-3-11-070368-9  SUP Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles